How should an API schema governance tool integrate with the software delivery lifecycle — specifically, at what points should different categories of validation run, what should block vs warn, and how should the tool balance shift-left principles with the reality that some validations are only meaningful in context?

The shift-left principle argues that catching issues early is cheaper than catching them late. A broken schema caught at the editor level costs seconds to fix. The same issue caught in production costs hours of debugging, potential data corruption, and customer impact. But naive application of shift-left — running all possible validations at every lifecycle stage — creates an unusable developer experience.

Think through which validation categories are appropriate at each lifecycle stage. At the editor/IDE level (real-time feedback as the developer types): only the fastest, highest-confidence, most context-insensitive checks. Syntax errors, missing required fields, invalid references. Never checks that require cross-file analysis or network access.

At the pre-commit hook level: checks that complete in under two seconds, have near-zero false positives on well-formed specs, and catch issues that would definitely fail CI. Schema structural validity, reference resolution, basic type consistency. Not: comprehensive security checks, compatibility checks against other versions, or style guide enforcement.

At the CI pull request check level: comprehensive validation, compatibility checking against the previous version, style guide enforcement, security checks, completeness scoring. Failures at this level block merge. This is the right place for checks that are thorough but potentially slow (up to 30 seconds).

At the deployment gate level: only the checks that are so critical that a previously-approved PR might still fail here — integration-test-based contract validation, runtime compatibility checks against a staging environment. This gate should almost never be triggered if CI is comprehensive, but it serves as a final safety net.

Think about the governance implications of this tiered model: who owns the rules at each tier, how are rule sets versioned and distributed, and how do organizations prevent individual teams from weakening CI checks to unblock their releases? What governance mechanisms make tiered validation durable rather than gradually eroding under delivery pressure?
